<ENAMEX TYPE="NORP">Turkish</ENAMEX> police announced yesterday that a terrorist group consisting of <ENAMEX TYPE="QUANTITY">10</ENAMEX> people has been disbanded .
The group included a lawyer who claimed in an interview with an <ENAMEX TYPE="NORP">Islamic</ENAMEX> magazine <ENAMEX TYPE="DATE">a year ago</ENAMEX> that he was the head of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG">Al - Qaeda</ENAMEX> organization in <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">Turkey</ENAMEX> .
The group also included <ENAMEX TYPE="QUANTITY">two</ENAMEX> members of the banned <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG">Knights of the Great Islamic Orient Front</ENAMEX> which claimed responsibility for the <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">Istanbul</ENAMEX> attacks , including the bombing of a <ENAMEX TYPE="NORP">Jewish</ENAMEX> temple and attacks on <ENAMEX TYPE="FAC">the British Consulate</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="FAC">the British HSBC bank</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="DATE">November 2003</ENAMEX> .
A security source said the police had kept the lawyer , whose name they did not disclose , under surveillance after he gave the press interview and located the remaining members of the network who contacted the lawyer through his email on the internet .
The source disclosed the existence of emails which talked about securing materials to make explosives and bombs and drawings and maps of <ENAMEX TYPE="NORP">Turkish</ENAMEX> oil refineries on the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOC">Mediterranean</ENAMEX> which it is believed were a target for the organization 's operations .
The police arrested <ENAMEX TYPE="NORP">Syrian</ENAMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Loay Saqa</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">Diyarbakir</ENAMEX> in <ENAMEX TYPE="DATE">August 2005</ENAMEX> on suspicion of being the assistant of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG">Al - Qaeda 's</ENAMEX> former leader in <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">Iraq</ENAMEX> , <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Abu Musab Al - Zarqawi</ENAMEX> , and <ENAMEX TYPE="NORP">Tunisian</ENAMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Malik Sharahil</ENAMEX> , both accused of plotting to blow up an <ENAMEX TYPE="NORP">Israeli</ENAMEX> tourist ship near the port of <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">Antalya</ENAMEX> , also on the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOC">Mediterranean</ENAMEX> .
They are currently being tried in <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE">Istanbul</ENAMEX> .
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Sharahil</ENAMEX> , who denied being a member of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG">Al - Qaeda</ENAMEX> , asked not to be deported to his country on the pretext that he would be sentenced to execution because of his affiliation with the banned <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG">Renaissance Party</ENAMEX> .
The security source said that a computer CD had been found in the <ENAMEX TYPE="NORP">Turkish</ENAMEX> lawyer 's house which laboratory tests revealed contained materials that would explode in the event of it being played , and this is the first time <ENAMEX TYPE="NORP">Turkish</ENAMEX> security forces have come across such explosives .
